## {{ rule.title }}

The Net Investment Income Tax under [26 U.S.C. § 1411](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section1411&num=0&edition=prelim) is a 3.8 % surtax on the lesser of (a) net investment income and (b) modified AGI minus the filing-status threshold. It is *separate* from regular income tax and is *not* offset by the foreign tax credit or treaty re-sourcing — it stacks on top.

For 2025:

- AGI (= modified AGI in this configuration): **{{ rule.inputs_by_key["us.income.adjusted_gross_income_usd"].value | money(currency="USD") }}**
- [§ 1411](https://uscode.house.gov/view.xhtml?req=granuleid:USC-prelim-title26-section1411&num=0&edition=prelim) threshold for your filing status: **{{ rule.inputs_by_key["us.filing_assumptions.niit_threshold_usd"].value | money(currency="USD") }}**
- Net investment income (dividends + interest + net capital gain + the elected substitute payments / staking inclusions): **{{ rule.inputs_by_key["us.tax.net_investment_income_usd"].value | money(currency="USD") }}**

Because NIIT is `3.8 % × min(net investment income, max(0, modified AGI − threshold))`:

- If AGI is at or below the threshold, the modified-AGI excess is zero and NIIT is zero — even with positive investment income.
- If investment income is below the modified-AGI excess, NIIT is `3.8 % × investment income`.
- Otherwise NIIT is `3.8 % × (modified AGI − threshold)`.

For your numbers, NIIT is **{{ rule.outputs[0].value | money(currency="USD") }}**. This appears on [Form 1040](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1040) Schedule 2 line 12 and [Form 8960](https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-8960) line 17.

